cts of their working lives – inequality of pay, the marriage bar and inequality of opportunity – and demonstrates how far wider cultural assumptions about womanhood shaped policies towards women’s employment and experiences. Scholars and students with interests in gender, British social and cultural history and labour history will find this an invaluable text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen in the civil servicexHistoryxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aWomen in the civil servicezGreat BritainxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aCivil Service.  aEmployment policy.  aFeminism.  aGender equality.  aLondon County Council.  aTrade unions and associations.  aTwentieth century.  aWar.  aWomen.  aWomen’s movement.  aWork.1 aGlew, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499682640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784996826423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784996826/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles